If you want GPU acceleration, stop this run cleanly

Because you need to uninstall/reinstall PyTorch, stop the current autocoder first.

Find the process:

Get-CimInstance Win32_Process |
  Where-Object {
    $_.Name -like "python*" -and
    $_.CommandLine -like "*naics_soc_laptop_tuned_autocoder.py*"
  } |
  Select-Object ProcessId, CreationDate, CommandLine |
  Format-List

Stop only that autocoder process:

Stop-Process -Id 12345

Replace 12345 with the actual process ID.

Do not stop the Positron language server process.

Confirm it is stopped:

Get-CimInstance Win32_Process |
  Where-Object {
    $_.Name -like "python*" -and
    $_.CommandLine -like "*naics_soc*autocoder.py*"
  } |
  Select-Object ProcessId, CreationDate, CommandLine |
  Format-List

You want zero autocoder processes before changing PyTorch.

Set up Hugging Face token or remove bad token noise

The warning says Hugging Face is unauthenticated. This is not fatal, but clean it up before rerunning.

If you have a read-only Hugging Face token:

$env:HF_TOKEN = "hf_your_real_token_here"

Use straight quotes, not curly quotes.

If you do not want to use a token right now:

Remove-Item Env:\HF_TOKEN -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

Hugging Face documents that HF_TOKEN overrides the token stored on the machine, so do not set it to an empty string.  

Install CUDA-enabled PyTorch

Your GPU is visible, but current PyTorch is CPU-only:

torch 2.11.0+cpu
cuda_is_available: false

First uninstall CPU-only torch:

cd C:\laborshed_autocode
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip uninstall -y torch torchvision torchaudio

Then install CUDA PyTorch.

Because your driver reports CUDA 12.8, I would first try the official PyTorch selector. Select:

OS: Windows
Package: Pip
Language: Python
Compute Platform: CUDA

and use the command it gives you. PyTorch’s site is the source of truth for the correct command.  

Given your nvidia-smi reports CUDA 12.8, a conservative install to try is CUDA 12.6:

python -m pip install torch torchvision torchaudio --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu126

Why CUDA 12.6? PyTorch’s release notes say CUDA 12.8 binaries are being removed in favor of CUDA 13.0 and CUDA 12.6, and they specifically mention switching pinned cu128 installs to cu130 or cu126. Since your driver reports CUDA 12.8, cu126 is the safer first try than cu130.  

If that fails because of Python 3.14 wheel availability, the practical fix is to create a Python 3.12 or 3.13 virtual environment for this project. I would not fight PyTorch wheel compatibility for days. The workhorse matters more than the paint on the barn.

